How To Properly Hand Write In Japanese
by Jerrid » Wed 09.29.2010 3:57 am I have a question regarding hand writing. I have learned a few spoken words in Japanese, but never how I would actually read them in Japanese. In the beginning lessons, the alphabets have a lot of extra... "nitches" in them. I do not know how to properly describe it, but looking at how it is hand writen and how it is typed, the typed versions is more easier to write, at least in my opinion. Not as much flair I assure you, but easier and quicker. If I were to write in Japanese as in a letter to some one, would I be expected to use the extra flair or would writing it as if it was typed acceptable. I have not even gotten far enough to see if this would even be an issue with actual written Japanese words, but I would be assuming it would. The only other way to describe this is like a capitalized "A" written is how it looks typed, at least standardly anyway. But add a little flair and the "A" would look like a "cursive A" which I do not know how to show a pic of here. Or maybe even better a description is with the lower case "a". Most people write it standardly with out the over hang at the top. But typed out you can clearly see the over hang in this forum. So does one need to learn the little "extra" strokes or just writing how it looks like when it is typed from a computer acceptable or even encouraged? (And I am not even talking about different fonts on computers, just standard stuff.) Thank you for your time and patience.
Jerrid
Posts: 14Joined: Wed 09.29.2010 2:37 am
Native language: English
